You have three independent API calls that can run concurrently. Which approach finishes fastest and correctly handles the case where all three must succeed before proceeding?

```js
// Option A
const a = await fetchA();
const b = await fetchB();
const c = await fetchC();

// Option B
const [a, b, c] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB(), fetchC()]);

// Option C
const [a, b, c] = await Promise.allSettled([fetchA(), fetchB(), fetchC()]);

// Option D
const a = fetchA();
const b = fetchB();
const c = fetchC();
```

A fetch call to an API returns a response with HTTP status 404. What does the following code log?

```js
try {
  const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/missing');
  const data = await res.json();
  console.log('success', data);
} catch (err) {
  console.log('caught', err.message);
}
```

Why does the following code NOT correctly increment the counter three times when the button is clicked?

